STEP 1: Identify exact cutoff for Q_k > 1
----------------------------------------

Q_k > 1 for k odd ⟺ 1/(4sin²(kπ/(2p))) > 1 ⟺ sin²(kπ/(2p)) < 1/4
⟺ |sin(kπ/(2p))| < 1/2 ⟺ kπ/(2p) < π/6 (first branch)
⟺ k < p/3

More precisely: k < p/3 OR k in (2p/3, p)
But k ∈ {1,...,m} = {1,...,(p-1)/2}, so k < p/2.
The condition k < p/3 covers the odd k with Q_k > 1 in this range.
For 5p/6 < k < p: sin(kπ/(2p)) = sin(π/2 - ε) ≈ 1, so Q_k < 1.

  p=97: odd k with Q>1: actual=16, predicted (k<p/3)=16, even k with Q>1=0
  p=997: odd k with Q>1: actual=166, predicted (k<p/3)=166, even k with Q>1=0

Perfect! The cutoff k < p/3 is exact for large p.
Odd k in {1,3,...,p/3}: approximately p/6 modes. Total m ≈ p/2.
Fraction = (p/6)/(p/2) = 1/3. ✓


STEP 2: Compute S(m) = Σ_{odd k < p/3} log Q_k
----------------------------------------

S(m) = Σ_{k odd, k<p/3} [-log 4 - 2 log sin(kπ/(2p))]

Let K = ⌊p/6⌋ = number of odd k values below p/3.
(Odd k in {1,3,...,2K-1}, so 2K-1 < p/3, K ≈ p/6.)

Cl_2(π/3) = 1.01494161
∫_0^{π/6} log sin t dt = -0.87040182
Numerical integral: -0.87045559


STEP 3: Assemble S(m)
----------------------------------------

S(m) ≈ (p/π)·Cl₂(π/3)

And log(F_p) ≈ (p-1)·log(φ) ≈ p·log(φ)

Therefore: κ = S(m)/log(F_p) ≈ Cl₂(π/3) / (π·log(φ))

κ_predicted = Cl₂(π/3) / (π·logφ) = 1.01494161 / (3.141593 × 0.481212)
            = 1.01494161 / 1.51177153
            = 0.6713591196

